  "why": "The metric evaluates two dimensions: semantic consistency and naturalness. Semantic consistency is not applicable here, as the paper employs a differential testing oracle which, by the metric's own definition, does not rely on semantic equivalence. The method scores 'High' on naturalness. The test cases (audio files) are generated from a corpus of natural text (the Europarl dataset) using a Text-to-Speech (TTS) system. The naturalness and plausibility of each generated audio are explicitly enforced through a cross-referencing mechanism: an audio-text pair is only considered a 'valid test case' if at least one ASR system in the reference set can correctly transcribe it. This filters out invalid or unnatural audios synthesized by the TTS system. Since each test case is generated independently from a natural text source and then validated for intelligibility, there is no iterative mutation and thus no risk of cumulative distortion or drift away from the original semantics or naturalness.",
